The paper proposes a method for air quality measurement based on deep learning, specifically using a double-channel convolutional neural network. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves feature extraction and fusion, which are common topics in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper mentions ensemble learning, which is a technique commonly used in neural networks and could place the paper in the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
